{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam,\" the poet evokes the memory of Islam's past heroes—the desert Arabs who built empires—most heroically in this climactic line: \"World-seizers and world-rulers, world-guardians and world-adorners.\"[^1] These ancestors embody collective, world-conquering action from humble origins, a legacy shaming the static modern youth.\n\nIn Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Andrew emerges as a present-tense hero through superhuman endurance of torture by the cannibalistic Mermedonians; his heroic apex amid relentless scourging is: \"his bone-house broken. Blood welled in waves, in hot gore. He had within him unwavering courage.\"[^2] This captures solitary defiance, faith, and bodily sacrifice in the moment.\n\n**Which ideal is harder to live up to?** Iqbal's demands emulating historical conquerors—ambitious, nation-building dynamism amid decline. Andrew's requires raw, immediate personal fortitude: unflinching under physical annihilation, without glory's promise. The latter strikes me as harder; glory fades into myth, but torture tests the soul now.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 13 \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-365462).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-34b202).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-74e29a).",
